Bed Layouts and Plant Counts

Bed 1 — North edge tall crops; south edge low crops

`
NORTH
EAST →──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────← WEST
      4 ft CORN (optional)   4 ft OKRA   20 ft TOMATOES + BASIL   4 ft EGGPLANT
┌────────────────────────┬────────────┬──────────────────────────┬──────────┐
│ CORN BLOCK (optional)  │   OKRA     │ TOMATOES + BASIL (20 ft) │ EGGPLANT │
├────────────────────────┴────────────┴──────────────────────────┴──────────┤
│                ITALIAN GREEN BEANS (south edge, full 32 ft)              │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
SOUTH
Width: 4 ft
`

Bed 1 Plant Counts
- Okra: 4–5 plants (18–24 in spacing)  
- Tomatoes: 8–10 plants (24–30 in spacing) — mix of Plum Regal, Juliet, Viva Italia, Sungold, Cherry 100  
- Basil: ~12 plants interplanted with tomatoes (12–18 in spacing)  
- Eggplant: 2 plants (18–24 in spacing)  
- Italian green beans: two offset rows along south edge (~60–80 seeds/plants)  
- Corn block (optional): 4 ft × 4 ft block = 16 plants (if you replace 4 ft of okra)

---

Bed 2 — Potatoes, carrots, strawberries, watermelon hill outside bed

`
NORTH
EAST →──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────← WEST
     10 ft POTATOES   2 ft CARROTS   20 ft STRAWBERRIES
┌──────────────────┬──────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┐
│    POTATOES      │   CARROTS    │            STRAWBERRIES             │
└──────────────────┴──────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┘
SOUTH
Width: 4 ft

Watermelon hill: plant at east or west end outside bed; train vines south over mulch.
`

Bed 2 Plant Counts
- Potatoes: ~10 seed pieces (12 in spacing; two rows)  
- Carrots: ~30–40 seeds (thin to 2–3 in)  
- Alpine strawberries: ~55–65 plants (10–12 in grid) — you have greenhouse seedlings ready  
- Watermelon: 1 hill outside bed (3–6 melons expected)

---

Crop Details

> Each crop entry includes start method, sow/transplant timing, depth, spacing, pH, water, height, production window, soil impact, and special notes.

---

Tomatoes (Plum Regal, Juliet, Viva Italia, Sungold, Cherry 100)
- Start method: Indoors 6–8 weeks before transplant.  
- Sow: late Jan → mid‑Feb for mid‑March transplant.  
- Transplant: mid‑March → early April after hardening.  
- Depth: bury to first true leaves (deep planting).  
- Spacing: 24–30 in.  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Consistent moisture; drip irrigation at root zone; avoid wet foliage.  
- Height: 3–6 ft (determinate shorter).  
- Production: June → October (peak midsummer).  
- Soil impact: Heavy feeder; side‑dress with compost; rotate away from potatoes.  
- Special: Use cages or stakes; prune minimally for determinate types.

---

Okra
- Start method: Direct sow after soil ≥65–70°F or start indoors 3–4 weeks earlier.  
- Sow: late April → May (soil warm).  
- Depth: 1 in.  
- Spacing: 18–24 in.  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Drought tolerant but performs best with regular deep watering.  
- Height: 3–6 ft.  
- Production: Late spring → fall; pick pods young.  
- Soil impact: Moderate feeder; deep roots help soil structure.

---

Italian Bush Green Beans
- Start method: Direct sow after last frost when soil >60°F.  
- Sow: mid‑April onward; succession every 2–3 weeks.  
- Depth: 1 in.  
- Spacing: 2–3 in seed spacing; rows 18–24 in.  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Even moisture; avoid waterlogging.  
- Height: 12–24 in.  
- Production: 50–70 days per sowing; multiple flushes.  
- Soil impact: Fixes nitrogen; excellent to follow heavy feeders.

---

Eggplant
- Start method: Indoors 6–8 weeks before transplant.  
- Transplant: mid‑March → April when nights >50°F.  
- Depth: same as pot depth.  
- Spacing: 18–24 in.  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Regular moisture; mulch to keep soil cool.  
- Height: 2–4 ft.  
- Production: Summer → early fall.  
- Soil impact: Heavy feeder; side‑dress with compost.

---

Potatoes
- Start method: Plant seed pieces early spring (Feb–Mar).  
- Depth: 4 in initial; hill soil as plants grow.  
- Spacing: 12 in.  
- pH: 5.5–6.5 preferred.  
- Water: Consistent moisture; avoid waterlogging.  
- Height: 12–24 in above ground.  
- Production: 10–16 weeks to new potatoes; main harvest mid‑summer.  
- Soil impact: Heavy feeder; replenish with compost or follow with legumes.

---

Carrots
- Start method: Direct sow early spring or fall (fall recommended in Texas).  
- Depth: 1/4–1/2 in.  
- Spacing: thin to 2–3 in.  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Steady moisture to avoid splitting.  
- Height: foliage 6–12 in.  
- Production: 60–80 days.  
- Soil impact: Light feeder; needs loose, stone‑free soil.

---

Alpine Strawberries
- Start method: Transplants from greenhouse now; harden off then plant.  
- Plant: early spring; spacing 10–12 in grid.  
- Depth: crown at soil level.  
- pH: 5.5–6.5.  
- Water: Keep soil moist; keep crowns dry.  
- Height: <12 in.  
- Production: Continuous April → November; perennial.  
- Soil impact: Low feeder; acts as living mulch.

---

Corn
- Start method: Direct sow mid‑April → May in blocks.  
- Depth: 1–2 in.  
- Spacing: 8–12 in; block planting (4×4 minimum).  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Heavy feeder — regular deep watering.  
- Height: 5–8+ ft.  
- Production: 60–100 days.  
- Soil impact: Strips nitrogen; follow with legumes or compost.

---

Watermelon
- Start method: Direct sow or transplant hills after soil ≥70°F (late April–May).  
- Depth: 1 in seed.  
- Spacing: hills 6 ft+; vines 8–15 ft.  
- pH: 6.0–6.8.  
- Water: Deep, infrequent watering; reduce near harvest.  
- Height: sprawling vines.  
- Production: 70–90 days; 3–6 melons per vigorous plant.  
- Soil impact: Moderate feeder; mulch runners over paths.

---

Spacing and Planting Depth Quick Reference

| Crop | Planting Depth | Spacing |
|------|----------------|---------|
| Tomatoes | bury to first true leaves | 24–30 in |
| Okra | 1 in | 18–24 in |
| Beans | 1 in | 2–3 in seeds; rows 18–24 in |
| Eggplant | same as pot | 18–24 in |
| Potatoes | 4 in then hill | 12 in |
| Carrots | 1/4–1/2 in | thin to 2–3 in |
| Strawberries | crown at soil level | 10–12 in grid |
| Corn | 1–2 in | 8–12 in; block planting |
| Watermelon | 1 in | hills 6 ft+ |

---

Irrigation Plan and Emitter Counts

General setup: two parallel 1/2" mainlines per bed spaced ~18 in apart; soaker lines for beans and carrots. Pressure regulator 15–20 PSI.

Bed 1 emitters (1 GPH unless noted)  
- Tomato row (20 ft): 20 emitters (12 in spacing)  
- Okra row (4–8 ft): 5–8 emitters (18 in spacing)  
- Eggplant (4 ft): 3 emitters (18 in spacing)  
- Beans (south edge 32 ft): soaker line or 32 emitters (12 in spacing)

Bed 2 emitters  
- Potatoes (10 ft): 10 emitters (12 in spacing)  
- Carrots (2 ft): soaker line  
- Strawberries (20 ft): 20 emitters (12 in spacing)  
- Watermelon hill: 2–3 emitters on a short spur

Run times starting points  
- Spring/Autumn: 20–30 min every other day.  
- Summer peak: 30–60 min daily (morning).  
- Mulched beds: reduce frequency; increase duration for deeper soak.

---

Month by Month Timeline and Tasks

January → February
- Start seeds indoors: tomatoes, eggplant, basil (6–8 weeks before transplant).  
- Potatoes: order seed potatoes; prep bed.  
- Greenhouse: pot up strawberry seedlings if needed.

March
- Harden off seedlings 7–10 days before transplant.  
- Transplant: tomatoes, eggplant, basil mid‑March → early April after hardening.  
- Plant potatoes early March if soil workable.  
- Install drip lines and test emitters.

April
- Direct sow: beans, corn (if soil warm), okra, watermelon hills after soil ≥70°F.  
- Mulch and side‑dress tomatoes with compost.  
- Begin pest scouting weekly.

May → June
- Succession sow beans every 2–3 weeks.  
- Tomato fruit set begins; support and prune as needed.  
- Increase irrigation as temperatures rise.

July → August
- Heat management: morning watering; temporary shade if needed.  
- Harvest: tomatoes, okra, beans, eggplant, early potatoes.  
- Strawberries: keep well watered in mornings.

September
- Final tomato flush; sow fall carrots early Sept.  
- Renovate strawberries if needed; add compost.

October → November
- Clean up spent foliage; compost healthy material.  
- Add compost and mulch to beds.  
- Plant garlic in Oct if desired.

December
- Tool maintenance, seed ordering, plan rotation.

---

Soil, Fertility, and Rotation

- At planting: incorporate 2 in compost into top 6–8 in.  
- Side‑dress: tomatoes and heavy feeders at fruit set and mid‑season.  
- After heavy feeders: add compost and plant legumes or cover crop.  
- pH targets: most crops 6.0–6.8; strawberries 5.5–6.5. Test annually.  
- Rotation: avoid planting tomatoes where potatoes were the previous year.

---

Pest, Disease, and Support Notes

- Tomatoes: cage or stake; scout for hornworms and blight; remove lower leaves.  
- Beans: watch for Mexican bean beetle.  
- Corn: stagger planting to reduce earworm pressure.  
- Watermelon: watch for powdery mildew; avoid overhead watering.  
- General: use row covers early season for flea beetles on eggplant; encourage beneficial insects with flowers.

---

Harvest, Processing, and Storage Notes

- Tomato sauce conversion: 2.5–3 lbs fresh tomatoes ≈ 1 quart finished sauce. With 120–250 lbs tomatoes expect ~40–100 quarts of sauce.  
- Okra: harvest young pods every 2–3 days; freeze blanched or pickle.  
- Strawberries: harvest daily at peak; freeze or preserve.  
- Potatoes: cure and store in cool, dark place.  
- Beans: blanch and freeze or can.

---

Checklists

Preseason checklist (Jan → Feb)
- [ ] Order seeds and seed potatoes.  
- [ ] Prepare raised beds and add compost.  
- [ ] Set up drip irrigation and pressure regulator.  
- [ ] Pot up greenhouse strawberry seedlings.

Transplant checklist (mid‑March)
- [ ] Harden off seedlings 7–10 days.  
- [ ] Transplant tomatoes, eggplant, basil, strawberries.  
- [ ] Mulch and set emitters.  
- [ ] Label rows and varieties.

Weekly growing season checklist
- [ ] Water according to schedule; adjust for heat.  
- [ ] Scout for pests and disease.  
- [ ] Harvest ripe produce.  
- [ ] Succession sow beans every 2–3 weeks.  
- [ ] Side‑dress heavy feeders as needed.

